/* CRISC :: content/pbqs.js — CRISC performance-based question database (30). */
window.CRISC = window.CRISC || {}; CRISC.pbqs = CRISC.pbqs || [];
CRISC.pbqs.push.apply(CRISC.pbqs, [
{"id":"PBQ-01","format":1,"domain":1,"obj":"1B3","title":"Placing accountability across the three lines","brief":"A recurring access-review control has failed its last two audit cycles, and the steering committee wants clarity on who is actually accountable for fixing it before the next cycle runs.","exhibitTitle":"WORKPAPER — CONTROL OWNERSHIP MAP","exhibit":"<span class='cy'>FIRST LINE:</span> Application owner in the claims division;\n  operates the quarterly access review manually.\n<span class='cy'>SECOND LINE:</span> Enterprise risk and compliance function;\n  sets the access-review policy and monitors completion rates.\n<span class='cy'>THIRD LINE:</span> Internal audit; tested the control and found\n  it was skipped for two consecutive quarters.\n<span class='dim'>Note: the application owner asks the risk function to just perform\n  the review going forward so audit \"stops flagging it.\"</span>","fields":[{"label":"Who should remain accountable for actually performing the access review?","hint":"First-line ownership of operational risk","options":["The application owner in the claims division, as the first-line risk and control owner","The second-line risk and compliance function, to guarantee it gets done","Internal audit, since it already knows the control best"],"answer":0,"explain":"The application owner is the first-line control owner who directly operates the business process and must retain accountability for performing the review; shifting execution to the second line would destroy the line-of-defense structure. The second-line risk and compliance function exists to set policy and monitor, not to operate first-line controls, so taking over execution would blur its oversight role. Internal audit is the third line providing independent assurance, and it cannot both perform a control and later audit it without losing the independence the model exists to protect."},{"label":"What should the second-line risk function do given the repeated audit failure?","hint":"Oversight and escalation, not execution","options":["Perform the review directly each quarter and stop reporting the gap","Escalate the pattern to the steering committee and reinforce the monitoring and accountability mechanism","Ignore the finding since it is the application owner's problem alone"],"answer":1,"explain":"Escalating the pattern to governance and strengthening monitoring is the correct second-line response: it keeps accountability with the first line while ensuring leadership is aware of a control that has now failed twice. Performing the review directly would have the risk function absorb an operational control it does not own, eliminating the very segregation the three lines model is designed to preserve. Ignoring the finding abandons the second line's core oversight responsibility and lets a known deficiency continue unaddressed."},{"label":"Why can internal audit not simply take over performing the review to guarantee compliance?","hint":"Independence cannot be self-assessed","options":["Because audit lacks the technical skill to review access lists","Because audit would then be assessing a control it operates itself, destroying its independence","Because audit is only permitted to review financial controls"],"answer":1,"explain":"If internal audit performed the control it is meant to independently assess, it would be auditing its own work, which eliminates the objectivity the third line exists to provide. The skill argument is not the issue; access reviews are well within audit's technical competence. The claim that audit only reviews financial controls is false; internal audit's mandate covers governance, risk management, and controls broadly, not just financial reporting."}]},
{"id":"PBQ-02","format":1,"domain":1,"obj":"1B5","title":"Setting risk tolerance bands beneath board-approved appetite","brief":"The board has approved an overall risk appetite statement, and the risk practitioner must now translate it into a workable tolerance band for a specific IT risk category before it can be used operationally.","exhibitTitle":"WORKPAPER — APPETITE-TO-TOLERANCE TRANSLATION","exhibit":"<span class='cy'>BOARD-APPROVED APPETITE:</span> \"Low appetite for risk\n  affecting regulated customer data; moderate appetite for risk\n  affecting internal productivity tools.\"\n<span class='cy'>PROPOSED TOLERANCE A:</span> A single tolerance band applied\n  uniformly to every system regardless of data sensitivity.\n<span class='cy'>PROPOSED TOLERANCE B:</span> A narrow tolerance band for\n  systems holding regulated customer data; a wider band for internal\n  productivity tools.\n<span class='dim'>Note: appetite is a board-level statement; tolerance operationalizes it.</span>","fields":[{"label":"Which tolerance proposal correctly operationalizes the board's stated appetite?","hint":"Tolerance should mirror differentiated appetite","options":["Proposal A, because uniform bands are simpler to administer","Proposal B, because it mirrors the board's differentiated appetite by data sensitivity","Neither; tolerance should always be wider than appetite to allow flexibility"],"answer":1,"explain":"Proposal B correctly reflects the board's differentiated appetite by setting a tighter tolerance band around regulated customer data and a looser one around lower-stakes internal tools, which is exactly what tolerance is supposed to do: operationalize appetite in measurable terms. Proposal A's uniform band ignores the board's explicit distinction and would either over-restrict low-risk systems or under-restrict regulated data, both undermining the appetite statement. The claim that tolerance should always be wider than appetite misunderstands the relationship; tolerance is the acceptable variation around the appetite level, not an automatic loosening of it."},{"label":"What should trigger management action once a specific risk is being measured against its tolerance band?","hint":"Tolerance is a threshold for action, not just observation","options":["Only when the risk exceeds the outer edge of its tolerance band","Any time the risk is discussed in a meeting, regardless of level","Never; tolerance bands are informational only and require no action"],"answer":0,"explain":"A tolerance band exists specifically to define the point at which deviation becomes unacceptable and management must act; crossing the outer edge is the defined trigger for a response. Requiring action merely because a risk is discussed makes the band meaningless, since routine discussion happens regardless of risk level. Treating tolerance as purely informational strips it of its operational purpose, which is to prompt a defined response when risk moves outside the acceptable range."},{"label":"Who is accountable for approving the initial risk appetite statement that tolerance bands must reflect?","hint":"Appetite-setting sits at the top of governance","options":["The IT risk practitioner drafting the tolerance bands","The board of directors or equivalent governing body","The application owners operating the affected systems"],"answer":1,"explain":"Risk appetite is a governance-level decision that only the board or an equivalent governing body can approve, since it reflects the organization's fundamental willingness to accept risk in pursuit of objectives. The risk practitioner's role is to translate that appetite into workable tolerance bands and metrics, not to set the appetite itself. Application owners operate within the approved tolerance but do not have the authority to define the enterprise-level appetite it derives from."}]},
{"id":"PBQ-03","format":1,"domain":1,"obj":"1A3","title":"Resolving an unowned enterprise-wide risk","brief":"A shared identity platform used by every business unit has a growing risk register entry, but no single department will accept accountability for it, each pointing to another as the rightful owner.","exhibitTitle":"WORKPAPER — RACI GAP ANALYSIS","exhibit":"<span class='cy'>FINDING:</span> Shared identity platform risk has no named\n  accountable owner in the RACI matrix; five business units use it.\n<span class='cy'>UNIT RESPONSES:</span> Each unit states the platform is \"IT's\n  system\" and declines to accept accountability.\n<span class='cy'>IT RESPONSE:</span> IT states it is only the technical custodian,\n  not the business risk owner.\n<span class='dim'>Note: risk has remained unassigned for three consecutive quarterly reviews.</span>","fields":[{"label":"What is the BEST way to resolve this cross-boundary ownership gap?","hint":"Shared services need a governance mechanism, not default drift","options":["Leave the risk unassigned since it affects multiple units equally","Escalate to a governance body, such as a steering committee, to formally assign accountable ownership","Assign it to IT by default since they operate the platform"],"answer":1,"explain":"When a risk spans multiple business units with no natural single owner, the correct resolution is escalation to a governance body with the authority to assign accountability, rather than letting the gap persist by default. Leaving the risk unassigned functionally means no one is making decisions about it, which is precisely the failure mode the RACI model exists to prevent. Defaulting to IT confuses the technical custodian role with business risk ownership; IT operates the platform but does not have the business context to weigh its risk appropriately."},{"label":"In RACI terms, what has gone wrong with this shared platform's accountability?","hint":"Diffusion of accountability across multiple parties","options":["Accountability has been diffused across multiple parties, leaving no single accountable owner","Too many parties are Responsible, which is a RACI violation by itself","The RACI matrix does not apply to shared or cross-functional assets"],"answer":0,"explain":"The core RACI failure here is that accountability has diffused across five business units and IT, none of whom accept it, when RACI requires exactly one Accountable party even if several are Responsible for doing the work. Having multiple Responsible parties is not itself a violation; RACI explicitly allows several people to share Responsible status. RACI absolutely applies to shared and cross-functional assets; in fact, such assets are precisely where a clear Accountable designation matters most."},{"label":"Once ownership is assigned, what should the practitioner build in to prevent this gap from recurring for other shared assets?","hint":"Systemic fix beyond this single incident","options":["A periodic ownership validation step in the risk register review cycle","Nothing further, since this specific platform's ownership is now resolved","A rule that only IT may ever own shared technology risks"],"answer":0,"explain":"Building periodic ownership validation into the standing review cycle catches orphaned or ambiguously owned risks systemically, rather than relying on someone noticing the gap by chance as happened here. Treating this single fix as sufficient ignores that other shared assets across the enterprise likely have the same unassigned-ownership problem. Mandating that IT always own shared technology risks as a blanket rule contradicts the earlier finding that IT is a custodian, not the appropriate business risk owner, and would recreate the same misassignment for other platforms."}]},
{"id":"PBQ-04","format":1,"domain":1,"obj":"1A6","title":"Sequencing resilience planning after a new critical process","brief":"A newly launched real-time payment processing service was not included in the last business continuity planning cycle, and leadership wants to know what governance step was missed.","exhibitTitle":"WORKPAPER — RESILIENCE GAP TIMELINE","exhibit":"<span class='cy'>MONTH 1:</span> Real-time payment service launched after\n  standard project approval; went live without a resilience review.\n<span class='cy'>MONTH 4:</span> A regional outage takes the service down for\n  six hours; no continuity plan existed for it.\n<span class='cy'>MONTH 5:</span> Post-incident review finds the service was never\n  routed through the organization's BCP intake process.\n<span class='dim'>Note: the BCP intake process exists and works for other services.</span>","fields":[{"label":"What is the root governance gap the post-incident review should highlight?","hint":"A working process that was bypassed, not a missing process","options":["The organization has no business continuity planning process at all","New initiatives are not being consistently routed through the existing BCP intake process before go-live","The regional outage itself was the root cause"],"answer":1,"explain":"The exhibit confirms a working BCP intake process exists for other services, so the root gap is that this new initiative was not routed through it before launch, not an absence of process entirely. Claiming no BCP process exists contradicts the stated fact that the intake process functions elsewhere in the organization. The regional outage is the triggering event that exposed the gap, not the underlying governance failure itself; the outage would have been survivable had continuity planning already covered the service."},{"label":"What should be corrected to prevent this from recurring with future new services?","hint":"Make the gate mandatory at the project lifecycle level","options":["Add a mandatory resilience and BCP intake gate to the project approval lifecycle for all new critical services","Rely on individual project managers to remember to loop in continuity planning","Only review resilience for services that have already experienced an outage"],"answer":0,"explain":"Embedding a mandatory resilience and BCP intake gate into the project lifecycle ensures every new critical service is evaluated before go-live, closing the systemic gap rather than depending on individual diligence. Relying on project managers to remember is exactly the informal approach that failed here and offers no structural guarantee. Waiting until a service has already experienced an outage before reviewing its resilience defeats the entire purpose of proactive continuity planning."},{"label":"Who should be accountable for ensuring the new payment service is added to the BCP going forward?","hint":"Business ownership of the process, not just IT","options":["The business process owner of the payment service, supported by the continuity planning function","The regional data center staff who experienced the outage","No one; resilience gaps are addressed only after the fact"],"answer":0,"explain":"The business process owner of the payment service is accountable for ensuring its criticality and recovery requirements are captured, working with the continuity planning function that facilitates the BCP process enterprise-wide. Data center staff experienced the operational symptom of the outage but are not accountable for the business-level continuity planning decision. Addressing resilience only reactively after incidents contradicts the entire premise of proactive business continuity governance."}]},
{"id":"PBQ-05","format":1,"domain":1,"obj":"1B7","title":"Aligning IT risk practice to a new regulatory obligation","brief":"A new data-localization law now requires certain customer records to remain within the country of origin, and the risk practitioner must determine how this obligation should be incorporated into IT risk governance.","exhibitTitle":"WORKPAPER — REGULATORY CHANGE INTAKE","exhibit":"<span class='cy'>NEW OBLIGATION:</span> Customer financial records must be\n  stored and processed within the country of origin, effective in 90 days.\n<span class='cy'>CURRENT STATE:</span> Records are currently replicated to a\n  central cloud region in a different country for disaster recovery.\n<span class='dim'>Note: legal has confirmed the obligation applies retroactively to\n  data already stored, not just new data going forward.</span>","fields":[{"label":"What is the risk practitioner's FIRST step upon learning of this new obligation?","hint":"Assess exposure before recommending architecture changes","options":["Immediately migrate all data to an in-country cloud region without further analysis","Assess the risk and compliance gap created by current cross-border replication and log it for structured treatment","Wait until the 90-day deadline is closer before taking any action"],"answer":1,"explain":"The correct first step is a structured risk and compliance gap assessment, capturing the exposure the current cross-border replication creates against the new obligation, so the response can be prioritized and resourced appropriately. Jumping straight to migration without assessing the full scope, dependencies, and disaster-recovery implications risks an unplanned, poorly sequenced change that could itself introduce new risk. Waiting until the deadline nears wastes the runway needed to plan and execute a compliant, low-risk transition within 90 days."},{"label":"Given the obligation applies retroactively, what must the risk register capture that a forward-looking-only reading would miss?","hint":"Existing exposure, not just new data flows","options":["That existing replicated records represent an active compliance gap requiring remediation, not just new data going forward","Nothing additional; only new data collected after the effective date matters","That the obligation can be satisfied simply by updating the privacy policy text"],"answer":0,"explain":"Because the obligation is retroactive, the register must capture that data already replicated cross-border constitutes an existing compliance gap right now, not merely a rule to apply to future data. Assuming only new data matters misreads the legal confirmation explicitly stated in the exhibit. Updating policy language does not change where data is physically stored or processed, so it cannot by itself satisfy a data-localization requirement."},{"label":"How should this obligation be reflected in ongoing IT risk governance beyond the immediate remediation?","hint":"Regulatory change is a recurring governance input, not a one-time fix","options":["As a one-time technical migration project with no lasting governance change","As a standing input to the compliance obligation inventory and future architecture and vendor decisions","It should not be reflected in governance since it is a legal, not an IT, matter"],"answer":1,"explain":"The obligation should be captured as a standing entry in the compliance obligation inventory so it continues to inform future architecture, disaster-recovery, and vendor decisions, not treated as a single project that concludes once the migration is done. Treating it as purely a one-time technical fix risks the same gap recurring the next time a new system or vendor is introduced without checking data-residency requirements. Dismissing it as solely a legal matter ignores that IT risk governance exists precisely to translate legal and regulatory obligations into enforceable technical and architectural requirements."}]},
{"id":"PBQ-06","format":1,"domain":1,"obj":"1B8","title":"Distinguishing governance decisions from management decisions","brief":"A risk practitioner is reviewing a batch of recent decisions to determine whether each was properly made at the governance level or the management level, and whether any require escalation.","exhibitTitle":"WORKPAPER — DECISION LOG REVIEW","exhibit":"<span class='cy'>DECISION 1:</span> The CIO independently approved accepting a\n  high-severity risk that exceeds the board's stated risk appetite.\n<span class='cy'>DECISION 2:</span> The steering committee ratified the annual IT\n  risk strategy submitted by the risk practitioner.\n<span class='cy'>DECISION 3:</span> A system administrator configured a firewall\n  rule change following the standard change-management process.","fields":[{"label":"Which decision represents a governance breakdown requiring escalation?","hint":"Management exceeding delegated authority","options":["Decision 1, because a management-level executive accepted risk beyond board-approved appetite without authorization","Decision 2, because ratifying strategy is not a governance activity","Decision 3, because firewall changes always require board approval"],"answer":0,"explain":"Decision 1 is the governance breakdown: accepting a risk that exceeds the board's stated appetite is a decision that exceeds the CIO's delegated management authority and should have been escalated to the board or its risk committee. Decision 2 is a legitimate governance activity; ratifying strategy against board-approved direction is exactly what a steering committee is meant to do. Decision 3 is a routine, appropriately delegated management action; firewall changes following standard change management do not require board involvement."},{"label":"What should have occurred instead of Decision 1 as described?","hint":"Escalation before acceptance","options":["The CIO should have delegated the decision further down to the system administrator","Nothing; CIOs always have authority to accept any level of risk","The CIO should have escalated the risk acceptance decision to the board or its risk committee given it exceeds delegated authority"],"answer":2,"explain":"Because the risk exceeds the appetite the board approved, the decision sits above the CIO's delegated authority and should have been escalated upward for governance-level acceptance, not made unilaterally. Delegating it further downward moves the decision away from, not toward, the appropriate level of authority. CIOs do not have unlimited authority to accept any level of risk; delegation of authority frameworks exist precisely to bound what a given role may decide independently."},{"label":"What governance artifact would have made this escalation threshold explicit in advance?","hint":"A documented delegation-of-authority framework","options":["An informal understanding among executives about what feels acceptable","A documented delegation-of-authority policy defining what risk levels require board versus management sign-off","The annual employee satisfaction survey"],"answer":1,"explain":"A documented delegation-of-authority policy that ties specific risk severity or financial thresholds to required approval levels removes ambiguity and gives the CIO a clear, pre-defined boundary for independent decision-making. An informal, undocumented understanding is precisely the kind of ambiguity that produces the ungoverned decision shown in Decision 1. An employee satisfaction survey has no relationship to risk-acceptance authority or escalation thresholds."}]},
{"id":"PBQ-07","format":1,"domain":1,"obj":"1A5","title":"Choosing the correct governance artifact for a mandatory security control","brief":"The organization needs to mandate a specific minimum password length and complexity across every system, and the practitioner must recommend which type of governance document should carry that requirement.","exhibitTitle":"WORKPAPER — GOVERNANCE ARTIFACT SELECTION","exhibit":"<span class='cy'>REQUIREMENT:</span> All systems must enforce a minimum\n  14-character password with defined complexity rules; mandatory,\n  not optional.\n<span class='cy'>OPTION 1:</span> Publish this as a policy statement alone,\n  with no further detail.\n<span class='cy'>OPTION 2:</span> Publish this as a standard, a specific,\n  mandatory technical requirement beneath the existing access-control\n  policy.\n<span class='cy'>OPTION 3:</span> Publish this as a guideline, offered as a\n  recommended but optional practice.","fields":[{"label":"Which artifact type correctly carries this specific, mandatory technical requirement?","hint":"Match the artifact's authority level to the requirement's specificity","options":["Option 1, since policies are meant to specify exact technical parameters","Option 2, a standard, since it states a specific, mandatory technical requirement beneath the broader policy","Option 3, since guidelines are the appropriate home for mandatory rules"],"answer":1,"explain":"A standard is precisely the artifact type meant to state a specific, mandatory technical requirement, such as an exact password length and complexity rule, sitting beneath a broader policy that establishes the general access-control mandate. Policies are high-level statements of intent and expected direction; they typically do not specify exact technical parameters like character counts. Guidelines are explicitly non-mandatory, recommended practices, which contradicts the requirement that this control be enforced everywhere without exception."},{"label":"What role does the higher-level access-control policy play relative to this new standard?","hint":"Policy sets direction; standards operationalize it","options":["The policy establishes the general mandate and intent that the standard then operationalizes with specific, enforceable detail","The policy and the standard are unrelated documents with no hierarchy between them","The standard replaces the need for the policy to exist at all"],"answer":0,"explain":"The policy sets the overarching mandate, such as requiring strong authentication generally, while the standard beneath it operationalizes that intent into specific, enforceable technical detail like the exact password rules, preserving a clear governance hierarchy. Treating them as unrelated ignores the standard hierarchy of policy, standard, procedure, and guideline that governance artifacts are built on. The standard does not replace the policy; it depends on and derives its authority from the policy's higher-level mandate."},{"label":"If a business unit requests an exception to this new standard for a legacy system that cannot support 14-character passwords, what should occur?","hint":"Exceptions still require governed evaluation","options":["The exception should be evaluated through the formal exception process, with a compensating control and appropriate approval","The standard should simply be lowered enterprise-wide to accommodate the legacy system","The business unit should be allowed to ignore the standard without any documentation"],"answer":0,"explain":"A legitimate technical constraint should be routed through the formal exception process, requiring a compensating control and approval from an authority with standing to accept the resulting risk, preserving governance over the deviation. Lowering the standard enterprise-wide to accommodate one legacy system unnecessarily weakens the control for every other system that could actually meet it. Allowing the business unit to ignore the standard without documentation creates an ungoverned gap that the very concept of a formal exception process exists to prevent."}]},
{"id":"PBQ-08","format":1,"domain":1,"obj":"1A7","title":"Prioritizing asset classification after an incomplete inventory is discovered","brief":"A newly hired risk practitioner discovers that the organization's asset inventory is missing an entire category of cloud-hosted development databases, none of which have ever been classified for sensitivity.","exhibitTitle":"WORKPAPER — ASSET INVENTORY GAP","exhibit":"<span class='cy'>FINDING:</span> 60 cloud-hosted development databases exist\n  outside the formal asset inventory; several contain copies of\n  production customer data used for testing.\n<span class='cy'>CURRENT STATE:</span> No owner, classification, or handling\n  requirement has ever been assigned to these databases.","fields":[{"label":"What is the risk practitioner's FIRST priority upon this discovery?","hint":"You cannot protect or govern what you cannot see","options":["Immediately delete all 60 databases to eliminate the exposure","Bring the databases into the formal asset inventory and classify them based on the sensitivity of the data they actually contain","Wait for the next annual inventory cycle to address the gap"],"answer":1,"explain":"The first priority is to bring these previously invisible assets into the formal inventory and classify them according to the sensitivity of the data they actually hold, since accurate classification is the prerequisite for any further risk-based decision about them. Deleting all 60 databases outright, without understanding their purpose or current use, risks destroying legitimate test environments and any recovery data they may hold. Waiting for the next annual cycle leaves an already-discovered, potentially sensitive exposure unaddressed for an unnecessarily long period."},{"label":"Why is it a significant finding that several databases contain copies of production customer data?","hint":"Classification and handling requirements follow the data, not the environment label","options":["Because \"development\" environments are automatically exempt from data-protection requirements","Because unclassified copies of sensitive production data in a lower-security development environment likely lack the access controls and protections the original data requires","Because development databases are always more secure than production databases"],"answer":1,"explain":"Development environments frequently have weaker access controls and monitoring than production, so unclassified copies of real customer data sitting there likely lack the protections that data's actual sensitivity requires, which is the core exposure this finding reveals. Assuming a \"development\" label exempts data from protection requirements is a common and dangerous misconception; classification should follow the data's actual sensitivity, not the environment's name. Development databases are not inherently more secure than production; they are frequently less rigorously controlled, which is exactly the concern here."},{"label":"What longer-term control should be established to prevent this kind of asset-inventory gap from recurring?","hint":"Make discovery continuous rather than periodic and manual","options":["A continuous or automated asset-discovery process integrated with provisioning, so new assets are captured and classified as they are created","Rely solely on the annual manual inventory review going forward","Prohibit all use of development databases across the organization"],"answer":0,"explain":"Integrating continuous or automated asset discovery with the provisioning process ensures new assets, including cloud resources spun up outside formal channels, are captured and classified as they are created rather than being found by chance later. Relying solely on an annual manual review is exactly the cadence that allowed 60 databases to go unnoticed and unclassified for an extended period. Prohibiting development databases entirely is a disproportionate response that would materially hinder legitimate testing activity rather than fixing the actual gap, which is visibility and classification, not the existence of test environments themselves."}]},
{"id":"PBQ-09","format":2,"domain":2,"obj":"2A4","title":"Building a well-formed risk scenario","brief":"An analyst has drafted a risk-register entry, and the practitioner must evaluate whether it is a properly constructed risk scenario before it is accepted into the register.","exhibitTitle":"WORKPAPER — DRAFT RISK SCENARIO","exhibit":"<span class='cy'>DRAFT ENTRY:</span> \"We might get hacked through the customer\n  portal.\"\n<span class='cy'>AVAILABLE DETAIL:</span> The customer portal (asset) runs an\n  outdated authentication library (vulnerability) that a known exploit\n  (threat) could use to bypass login, exposing customer PII and\n  triggering regulatory fines and remediation costs (impact).\n<span class='dim'>Note: the draft entry omits nearly all of the available detail.</span>","fields":[{"label":"What is the primary deficiency of the draft entry as written?","hint":"Vague statements cannot be assessed or tracked","options":["It is too short to fit in the register's title field","It fails to name the asset, threat, vulnerability, and impact needed to make the risk assessable and actionable","It uses the word \"hacked,\" which is not permitted terminology"],"answer":1,"explain":"A well-formed risk statement must explicitly name the asset at risk, the threat, the exploitable vulnerability, and the business impact; the draft entry omits all of this available detail, making it impossible to assess, prioritize, or assign ownership. Field length is not the issue; the entry could be rewritten concisely while still including the necessary elements. Word choice is a stylistic concern, not the substantive reason this entry is unusable as a risk-register record."},{"label":"Which rewritten version of the entry would be a properly formed risk scenario?","hint":"Name asset, threat, vulnerability, and impact explicitly","options":["\"IT security is generally weak and needs improvement.\"","\"The customer portal's outdated authentication library could be exploited by a known attack to bypass login, exposing customer PII and triggering regulatory fines.\"","\"Hacking is a common problem in our industry.\""],"answer":1,"explain":"This version names the specific asset (customer portal), vulnerability (outdated authentication library), threat (a known exploit), and impact (exposed PII, regulatory fines), giving the register everything needed to assess and treat the risk. The first alternative is a vague generalization with no specific asset, threat, or vulnerability named. The second alternative describes an industry trend, not a scenario specific to this organization's actual exposure."},{"label":"Once properly formed, what should this risk scenario be scored against before treatment is decided?","hint":"Analysis precedes response","options":["Its likelihood and impact, established through qualitative or quantitative assessment","The personal opinion of whichever executive reviews it first","Nothing; a well-formed scenario is automatically escalated to the board"],"answer":0,"explain":"Once the scenario is properly formed, it must be assessed for likelihood and impact using qualitative or quantitative analysis before a response decision is made, which is the standard sequence from identification through analysis to treatment. Relying on a single executive's opinion reintroduces the subjectivity and lack of rigor that a structured scenario is meant to avoid. Not every well-formed risk scenario warrants board-level escalation; escalation should depend on the resulting risk level, not merely on the scenario being well-written."}]},
{"id":"PBQ-10","format":2,"domain":2,"obj":"2B6","title":"Distinguishing inherent, current, and residual risk after a control failure","brief":"A control that reduced a data-exfiltration risk has just failed silently for several months, and the practitioner must correctly reassess the risk levels in the register.","exhibitTitle":"WORKPAPER — CONTROL FAILURE RISK RECALCULATION","exhibit":"<span class='cy'>INHERENT RISK:</span> Rated High (before any controls existed).\n<span class='cy'>PRIOR RESIDUAL RISK:</span> Rated Low, based on a data loss\n  prevention control assumed to be operating effectively.\n<span class='cy'>NEW FINDING:</span> The DLP control has been silently disabled\n  by a configuration change for four months.\n<span class='dim'>Note: no compensating control was in place during this period.</span>","fields":[{"label":"What should the register reflect as the CURRENT risk level once the control failure is discovered?","hint":"Current risk reflects real-time control effectiveness","options":["It should remain rated Low, matching the prior residual risk assessment","It should be reassessed toward the inherent High level, since the control was not actually operating during this period","It should be rated at whatever level is easiest to report to the board"],"answer":1,"explain":"Current risk must reflect the risk level given controls as they are actually operating right now, and since the DLP control was silently disabled with no compensating control, the current risk should move back toward the inherent High level for the period it was not functioning. Leaving it at the prior Low residual rating would misrepresent an assumed control that was not, in fact, providing protection. Choosing whatever level is easiest to report abandons the entire discipline of evidence-based risk assessment in favor of convenience."},{"label":"Why does the inherent risk rating NOT change as a result of this discovery?","hint":"Inherent risk is defined as risk with no controls at all","options":["Inherent risk is fixed and never needs to be reviewed again once initially scored","Inherent risk represents exposure with no controls applied, and control failures do not alter that baseline definition","Inherent risk should now be rated Low to match the mistaken assumption"],"answer":1,"explain":"Inherent risk is defined as the exposure that would exist with no controls in place at all, so whether a control is working, failing, or absent has no bearing on that baseline figure; only residual and current risk move with control performance. Claiming inherent risk never needs review conflates it with residual risk, which does require ongoing reassessment as controls and conditions change. Rating inherent risk as Low would incorrectly import the very control-dependent assumption that inherent risk is specifically designed to exclude."},{"label":"What should be reported to the risk owner given this finding?","hint":"Transparency about the true exposure during the failure window","options":["That the risk was effectively at a much higher level than reported for the duration of the silent failure, along with corrective and monitoring actions","Nothing, since no confirmed data loss has been reported yet","Only that the configuration has now been fixed, without discussing the historical exposure window"],"answer":0,"explain":"The risk owner needs a transparent, accurate picture that the true exposure was substantially higher than the reported Low rating throughout the four-month silent failure, along with the corrective action taken and any new monitoring to prevent recurrence. Withholding this because no confirmed loss has surfaced ignores that the elevated exposure existed regardless of whether it was exploited. Reporting only that the fix is complete, without disclosing the historical exposure window, denies the risk owner the information needed to assess whether further action, such as a retrospective investigation, is warranted."}]},
{"id":"PBQ-11","format":2,"domain":2,"obj":"2B5","title":"Computing ALE and evaluating a proposed control","brief":"The practitioner must calculate the annualized loss expectancy for a specific risk scenario and determine whether a proposed control is a financially justified investment.","exhibitTitle":"WORKPAPER — QUANTITATIVE RISK INPUTS","exhibit":"<span class='cy'>ASSET VALUE (AV):</span> $1,500,000 (order management system,\n  including downtime and recovery cost impact).\n<span class='cy'>EXPOSURE FACTOR (EF):</span> 0.30 (30% of value lost per\n  successful ransomware event).\n<span class='cy'>ANNUALIZED RATE OF OCCURRENCE (ARO):</span> 0.20 (expected once\n  every five years based on industry data).\n<span class='cy'>PROPOSED CONTROL COST:</span> $50,000 per year; projected to\n  reduce ARO to 0.05.","fields":[{"label":"What is the Single Loss Expectancy (SLE) for this scenario?","hint":"SLE = AV × EF","options":["$450,000","$1,500,000","$300,000"],"answer":0,"explain":"SLE = AV × EF = $1,500,000 × 0.30 = $450,000, which is the expected loss from a single occurrence of this event. $1,500,000 is simply the asset value with no exposure factor applied, ignoring that only a portion of value would be lost per event. $300,000 does not result from correctly multiplying the given asset value and exposure factor."},{"label":"What is the current Annualized Loss Expectancy (ALE) before the proposed control is implemented?","hint":"ALE = SLE × ARO","options":["$22,500","$450,000","$90,000"],"answer":2,"explain":"ALE = SLE × ARO = $450,000 × 0.20 = $90,000, representing the expected annual loss from this risk under current conditions. $450,000 is the SLE itself, before annualizing by the rate of occurrence. $22,500 does not follow from correctly multiplying the calculated SLE by the stated ARO."},{"label":"Is the proposed $50,000 control a financially justified investment based on the projected ARO reduction?","hint":"Compare risk reduction to control cost","options":["Yes, because any control that reduces ARO is automatically worth its cost regardless of the numbers","No, because ALE calculations are never a valid basis for control investment decisions","No, because the new ALE of $22,500 yields only $67,500 in risk reduction against a $50,000 cost, a thinner margin than it first appears but still positive"],"answer":2,"explain":"With ARO reduced to 0.05, the new ALE is $450,000 × 0.05 = $22,500, so the risk reduction is $90,000 − $22,500 = $67,500 against a $50,000 annual control cost, a positive but modest return that the practitioner should present with the full numbers rather than a simple yes/no. Assuming any ARO-reducing control is automatically worth its cost ignores the need to actually compare the dollar figures, which is the entire point of quantitative analysis. Dismissing ALE as never valid for investment decisions contradicts its standard, well-established use for exactly this kind of cost-benefit comparison."}]},
{"id":"PBQ-12","format":2,"domain":2,"obj":"2B7","title":"Prioritizing risks on a heat map with tied ratings","brief":"Two risks land in the same cell on the qualitative heat map, and the practitioner must determine how to prioritize between them for limited remediation resources this quarter.","exhibitTitle":"WORKPAPER — HEAT MAP TIE-BREAK","exhibit":"<span class='cy'>RISK A:</span> Rated High likelihood / Moderate impact; affects\n  an internal reporting tool with no regulated data.\n<span class='cy'>RISK B:</span> Rated High likelihood / Moderate impact; affects\n  a system processing regulated healthcare data.\n<span class='dim'>Both risks land in the same heat-map cell and carry the same\n  ordinal rating.</span>","fields":[{"label":"Given the tie on the heat map, what additional factor should drive prioritization?","hint":"Heat maps compress information; look beneath the color","options":["Whichever risk was entered into the register first","Alphabetical order of the risk titles","The nature of the asset and data involved, since regulated healthcare data carries materially higher consequence and regulatory exposure"],"answer":2,"explain":"Even though both risks land in the same ordinal heat-map cell, Risk B's exposure of regulated healthcare data carries materially greater regulatory, legal, and reputational consequence than Risk A's internal reporting tool, and that qualitative distinction should break the tie in favor of treating Risk B first. Alphabetical order has no connection to actual risk severity and would be an arbitrary basis for prioritization. Entry date reflects administrative timing, not the comparative business consequence that should drive remediation sequencing."},{"label":"What does this tie reveal about the limitation of a purely ordinal heat map?","hint":"Ordinal ratings compress important distinctions","options":["Heat maps always produce perfectly distinct priorities with no possible ties","Heat maps can compress meaningfully different risks into the same cell, masking distinctions that matter for prioritization","Heat maps should never be used for any risk with a High likelihood rating"],"answer":1,"explain":"This scenario demonstrates exactly why ordinal heat maps have a known limitation: two risks with genuinely different real-world consequence can land in the identical cell, and the practitioner must look past the color to the underlying context to prioritize correctly. Claiming heat maps always produce distinct priorities is contradicted directly by this tied example. Avoiding heat maps entirely for high-likelihood risks throws away a useful prioritization tool over a limitation that can be managed with supplementary judgment instead."},{"label":"Should this tie-break analysis be documented in the risk register?","hint":"Prioritization rationale should be traceable","options":["No, informal reasoning is sufficient and does not need to be recorded","Yes, the rationale for prioritizing Risk B over Risk A should be documented so the decision is traceable and defensible later","No, documenting reasoning would slow down the remediation process unnecessarily"],"answer":1,"explain":"Documenting the rationale for prioritizing Risk B ensures the decision is traceable and defensible if questioned later, for example during an audit or when a stakeholder from Risk A's business unit asks why their item was deprioritized. Relying on informal, undocumented reasoning leaves the organization unable to reconstruct or justify the decision after the fact. Documentation is a brief, low-cost step and does not meaningfully slow remediation, while its absence creates a governance gap of its own."}]},
{"id":"PBQ-13","format":2,"domain":2,"obj":"2A2","title":"Scoping a threat model to the organization's actual exposure","brief":"A threat intelligence briefing lists a broad set of nation-state, criminal, and hacktivist threats, and the practitioner must determine which of these should shape the organization's own risk scenarios.","exhibitTitle":"WORKPAPER — THREAT LANDSCAPE RELEVANCE FILTER","exhibit":"<span class='cy'>BRIEFING:</span> Lists nation-state espionage campaigns\n  targeting defense contractors, organized ransomware crews\n  targeting mid-size retailers, and hacktivist defacement campaigns\n  targeting government sites.\n<span class='cy'>ORGANIZATION PROFILE:</span> A mid-size retail chain with no\n  government or defense contracts.","fields":[{"label":"Which threat category from the briefing is MOST relevant to this organization's risk scenarios?","hint":"Match threat actor motive and target profile to the organization's actual profile","options":["Nation-state espionage targeting defense contractors, since nation-state threats are always the highest priority to model","Organized ransomware crews targeting mid-size retailers, since this matches the organization's actual sector and size profile","Hacktivist defacement targeting government sites, since defacement is the most visible threat type"],"answer":1,"explain":"The ransomware threat targeting mid-size retailers directly matches this organization's actual sector and size profile, making it the most relevant category to translate into specific risk scenarios for the register. Nation-state espionage against defense contractors has essentially no plausible path to this retailer, which holds no government or defense contracts; treating all nation-state threats as automatically top priority ignores relevance to the specific organization. Hacktivist defacement of government sites targets a completely different victim profile and is not indicated as relevant to a private retail chain."},{"label":"Why is it important to filter the threat landscape by relevance rather than tracking every reported threat equally?","hint":"Unfiltered intelligence produces noise, not insight","options":["Because tracking every threat equally produces noise that obscures the few threats actually applicable to the organization's assets and vulnerabilities","Because filtering is unnecessary; all threats are equally likely for every organization","Because only the most recently published threat intelligence report ever matters"],"answer":0,"explain":"Filtering the threat landscape for relevance to the organization's own assets, sector, and vulnerabilities converts a flood of intelligence into a manageable number of decisions, whereas tracking every reported threat equally buries the genuinely applicable ones in noise. Claiming all threats are equally likely for every organization ignores that threat actors choose targets based on motive and opportunity, which vary significantly by sector and profile. Recency of publication is not the relevant filter; applicability to the organization's actual exposure is what matters, regardless of how new or old the intelligence is."},{"label":"What should the practitioner do with the nation-state and hacktivist threat categories that do not currently apply?","hint":"Document the relevance decision rather than discarding it silently","options":["Discard them permanently with no record, since they clearly do not apply today","Document that they were assessed and found not currently relevant, revisiting if the organization's profile changes (e.g., a future government contract)","Escalate them to the board immediately as active risks regardless of relevance"],"answer":1,"explain":"Documenting that these categories were assessed and found not currently relevant preserves the analysis trail and allows a fast, informed re-evaluation if the organization's profile changes, such as pursuing a future government contract that would suddenly make nation-state threats relevant. Discarding them with no record at all loses the rationale and forces the same analysis to be redone from scratch later. Escalating clearly inapplicable threats to the board as active risks would misrepresent the organization's actual exposure and dilute attention from the threats that genuinely apply today."}]},
{"id":"PBQ-14","format":2,"domain":2,"obj":"2B2","title":"Using BIA findings to challenge an inflated criticality claim","brief":"A system owner insists their application is \"mission critical\" and should receive the shortest possible recovery time objective, but the practitioner's BIA interview reveals the claim is not well supported by actual business consequence.","exhibitTitle":"WORKPAPER — BIA CRITICALITY CHALLENGE","exhibit":"<span class='cy'>OWNER CLAIM:</span> \"This system is mission critical; it needs\n  a 30-minute RTO.\"\n<span class='cy'>BIA INTERVIEW FINDING:</span> When asked what specifically\n  happens at hour 1, hour 4, and hour 24 of an outage, the owner\n  could only describe a \"delay in generating a weekly summary\n  report,\" with no financial, regulatory, or safety consequence identified.\n<span class='dim'>Note: no other business process depends on this system's real-time availability.</span>","fields":[{"label":"How should the practitioner respond to the gap between the owner's claim and the BIA interview findings?","hint":"Criticality is derived from business consequence, not advocacy","options":["Accept the owner's stated 30-minute RTO at face value, since system owners always understand their own criticality best","Challenge the claim with the evidence gathered and set the RTO based on the actual, modest business consequence described, not the unsupported assertion","Split the difference and assign an arbitrary RTO between the owner's claim and a fully relaxed target"],"answer":1,"explain":"The practitioner should challenge the inflated claim using the evidence-based findings from the interview and set the RTO to reflect the system's actual, modest business consequence, since a delayed weekly report is a minor operational inconvenience, not a mission-critical failure. Accepting the claim at face value ignores that the BIA process specifically exists to test and validate criticality claims against real consequence, not simply record self-reported priority. Splitting the difference arbitrarily abandons the evidence gathered entirely in favor of an unprincipled compromise with no basis in actual business impact."},{"label":"Why do system owners sometimes overstate criticality during a BIA interview?","hint":"Incentives can distort self-reported priority","options":["Because owners believe a higher priority ranking guarantees more recovery investment and attention for their system","Because BIA interviews are designed to reward the most dramatic claims","Because overstating criticality is required by the BIA methodology itself"],"answer":0,"explain":"System owners often overstate criticality because they believe, correctly or not, that a higher-priority ranking will translate into more recovery investment, budget, and organizational attention for their system, which creates an incentive to inflate the claim. BIA interviews are not designed to reward drama; they are designed to extract objective, evidence-based impact data through structured, skeptical questioning. Overstating criticality is not required by the methodology; the methodology's entire purpose is to test claims against genuine business consequence, as this scenario demonstrates."},{"label":"What should the practitioner do to keep criticality rankings comparable across many interviewed system owners?","hint":"Consistency prevents the ranking from reflecting advocacy rather than reality","options":["Apply the same evidence-based questioning technique and consistent impact scale to every system owner interviewed, regardless of how forcefully they advocate","Allow each system owner to define their own criticality scale independently","Rank systems solely by how senior the requesting owner is within the organization"],"answer":0,"explain":"Applying the same rigorous, evidence-based questioning and a consistent impact scale across every interview ensures the resulting criticality ranking reflects genuine business consequence rather than differences in how persuasively different owners advocated for their own systems. Allowing each owner to define their own scale destroys comparability across the register, making it impossible to rank systems meaningfully against each other. Ranking by the requester's seniority substitutes organizational politics for actual business impact, which is precisely the bias a rigorous BIA process is meant to eliminate."}]},
{"id":"PBQ-15","format":3,"domain":3,"obj":"3A1","title":"Selecting the best risk response for a catastrophic, hard-to-control exposure","brief":"A regional manufacturing subsidiary faces a low-likelihood but potentially catastrophic risk from a single-source raw-material supplier located in an area prone to natural disasters, and the practitioner must recommend a response.","exhibitTitle":"WORKPAPER — RESPONSE OPTIONS FOR SUPPLIER RISK","exhibit":"<span class='cy'>RISK:</span> Sole-source raw-material supplier located in a\n  high-disaster-risk region; a disruption would halt production\n  for an estimated 4-6 months with no viable alternate supplier\n  identified.\n<span class='cy'>OPTION 1:</span> Continue building redundant on-site inventory\n  buffers indefinitely (high, recurring carrying cost).\n<span class='cy'>OPTION 2:</span> Purchase business interruption and supply-chain\n  insurance covering this specific exposure.\n<span class='cy'>OPTION 3:</span> Discontinue the product line dependent on this\n  supplier entirely.","fields":[{"label":"Which response BEST fits this low-likelihood, high-impact, hard-to-control exposure?","hint":"Insurance exists precisely for this profile","options":["Option 1, since more inventory always reduces supply risk proportionally","Option 2, transferring the catastrophic financial tail through insurance since no cost-effective mitigation eliminates the exposure","Option 3, since avoidance is always preferable when a supplier cannot be easily replaced"],"answer":1,"explain":"A low-likelihood, high-impact risk that resists practical mitigation is the classic profile for risk transfer through insurance, funding the rare but severe loss without the ongoing cost of over-mitigating or the business cost of avoidance. Indefinite inventory buffering carries a high recurring cost that does not scale efficiently against a rare event and does not address the underlying single-source dependency. Discontinuing the product line is a disproportionate response given the low likelihood; avoidance should be reserved for risks where no reasonable transfer or mitigation brings exposure within tolerance, which is not established here."},{"label":"What secondary risk should the practitioner evaluate before finalizing the insurance-based response?","hint":"Transfer does not eliminate every consequence","options":["Whether the policy's sublimits, deductible, and exclusions leave a material gap between the insured amount and the actual 4-6 month loss","Whether the insurer's logo appears professional on marketing materials","Whether the supplier will be offended that insurance was purchased"],"answer":0,"explain":"Insurance transfers financial consequence, but only up to its actual terms, so the practitioner must verify the sublimits, deductible, and exclusions do not leave a material gap relative to the estimated 4-6 month production loss, since transfer that under-covers the real exposure is a false sense of security. The insurer's branding has no bearing on risk management. Supplier sentiment about the customer's insurance purchase is not a risk factor relevant to this decision."},{"label":"Even after purchasing insurance, what residual risk must still be formally accepted by the risk owner?","hint":"Transfer rarely reaches zero residual risk","options":["The operational and reputational impact of a multi-month production halt that insurance payouts do not directly prevent","No residual risk remains once insurance is purchased","The risk owner's role ends once the insurance premium is paid"],"answer":0,"explain":"Insurance addresses the financial consequence but does not prevent the operational disruption itself or the reputational and customer-relationship damage from a multi-month halt, so that residual exposure must still be explicitly accepted by the accountable risk owner. Claiming no residual risk remains ignores that transfer virtually never reduces risk to zero. The risk owner's accountability continues after the premium is paid; ongoing monitoring and periodic reassessment of the arrangement remain the owner's responsibility."}]},
{"id":"PBQ-16","format":3,"domain":3,"obj":"3A4","title":"Managing a growing population of policy exceptions","brief":"The exception log shows the same encryption-at-rest control being waived repeatedly by different business units, each renewal citing a different short-term business justification.","exhibitTitle":"WORKPAPER — EXCEPTION PORTFOLIO REVIEW","exhibit":"<span class='cy'>CONTROL:</span> Mandatory encryption at rest for databases\n  holding customer data.\n<span class='cy'>EXCEPTION HISTORY:</span> 14 active exceptions against this\n  control across 6 business units, several renewed 3+ times with\n  no remediation progress.\n<span class='dim'>Note: each exception was individually approved with a documented\n  business justification and a compensating control at the time.</span>","fields":[{"label":"What does this pattern of exceptions most strongly suggest?","hint":"Volume and repetition are a diagnostic signal","options":["That each exception was properly handled individually, so no further action is needed","That the control itself may be poorly calibrated to operational reality and should be reviewed, or that these have become unacknowledged risk acceptances requiring explicit decision","That encryption at rest should be abandoned as a control entirely"],"answer":1,"explain":"A large, repeatedly renewed exception population against the same control is a diagnostic signal that either the control needs to be redesigned to fit operational reality, or that these renewals have quietly become de facto permanent risk acceptances that were never explicitly decided as such, and both possibilities warrant a genuine accept-or-remediate decision now. Treating each exception as properly closed individually misses the systemic pattern the aggregate portfolio reveals. Abandoning the control entirely overreacts and removes a legitimate protection rather than addressing why compliance keeps failing."},{"label":"What should accompany any further renewal of these exceptions?","hint":"Prevent indefinite renewal from masking real exposure","options":["Nothing different; renewals can continue indefinitely as long as a justification is written each time","A genuine reassessment of whether remediation is actually feasible, with escalation to the appropriate authority if the exception is effectively permanent","Automatic approval without review, since the control has already been waived before"],"answer":1,"explain":"Any further renewal should trigger a genuine reassessment of whether the underlying gap can realistically be remediated, and if it cannot, the practitioner should escalate for an explicit, informed risk-acceptance decision rather than letting indefinite renewal quietly substitute for one. Allowing renewals to continue indefinitely on the same justification is exactly the pattern that obscures a de facto permanent acceptance. Automatic approval without review abandons the risk evaluation an exception process is supposed to provide."},{"label":"What governance action should follow from recognizing this as a systemic issue rather than six isolated ones?","hint":"Root-cause fix, not repeated point fixes","options":["Investigate the common root cause across business units and consider redesigning the control or its implementation approach enterprise-wide","Approve each of the 14 exceptions for another year and revisit next cycle","Assign blame to the business unit with the most exceptions and stop there"],"answer":0,"explain":"Recognizing 14 exceptions against one control as a systemic pattern calls for root-cause investigation across the affected business units and likely a redesign of the control or its implementation approach, rather than treating each as an unrelated, isolated waiver. Simply re-approving all 14 for another year repeats the same deferral that created this backlog in the first place. Assigning blame to a single business unit ignores that the pattern spans six units, pointing to a shared underlying cause rather than one unit's individual failure."}]},
{"id":"PBQ-17","format":3,"domain":3,"obj":"3A5","title":"Evaluating whether a risk acceptance was properly authorized","brief":"A director accepted a risk on behalf of the organization that, on closer review, appears to exceed the financial threshold delegated to that role under the organization's authority framework.","exhibitTitle":"WORKPAPER — RISK ACCEPTANCE AUTHORITY CHECK","exhibit":"<span class='cy'>ACCEPTANCE:</span> Director signed off accepting a risk with an\n  estimated potential loss of $8 million.\n<span class='cy'>DELEGATION FRAMEWORK:</span> Directors may accept risk up to\n  $2 million; risks above that threshold require executive committee\n  or board sign-off.\n<span class='dim'>Note: the acceptance has already been recorded in the risk register\n  as \"closed - accepted.\"</span>","fields":[{"label":"What is the core problem with this risk acceptance as recorded?","hint":"Authority limits exist for a reason","options":["The acceptance was made by someone without the delegated authority to accept a risk of this magnitude","The acceptance is fine since it was documented and signed","The risk register entry is invalid because it says \"closed\" instead of \"resolved\""],"answer":0,"explain":"The director's authority under the delegation framework caps at $2 million, so accepting an $8 million risk exceeds that delegated limit and requires escalation to the executive committee or board regardless of how properly the acceptance was otherwise documented. Being documented and signed does not cure an authority gap; a well-written acceptance made outside the signer's authority is still improperly authorized. The specific wording used for the register status is a cosmetic detail, not the substantive governance failure here."},{"label":"What should the risk practitioner do upon discovering this authority mismatch?","hint":"Escalate, do not simply let the acceptance stand","options":["Leave the acceptance as recorded since reopening it would be administratively inconvenient","Escalate the acceptance to the executive committee or board for a properly authorized decision, correcting the register accordingly","Quietly lower the estimated loss figure to bring it under the director's threshold"],"answer":1,"explain":"The practitioner should escalate the acceptance to the body with actual authority over risks of this magnitude, ensuring a properly authorized decision is made and the register is corrected to reflect it accurately. Leaving an improperly authorized acceptance in place perpetuates a governance gap regardless of administrative convenience. Altering the loss estimate to artificially fit under the director's threshold would be a fabrication that defeats the entire purpose of a delegation-of-authority control."},{"label":"What control should be strengthened to prevent this authority mismatch from recurring?","hint":"Systemic control, not a one-time correction","options":["A validation step in the acceptance workflow that checks estimated loss against the accepting role's delegated threshold before allowing sign-off","Removing all authority limits so any manager can accept any risk level","Requiring the board to personally review and approve every risk acceptance regardless of size"],"answer":0,"explain":"Adding a validation check to the acceptance workflow itself, comparing the estimated loss against the accepting role's threshold before allowing sign-off, closes this gap systemically rather than relying on someone to catch it after the fact. Removing authority limits entirely would eliminate the very control that exists to prevent under-authorized acceptances. Requiring board review of every acceptance regardless of size is disproportionate and would overwhelm the board with routine, low-risk decisions that delegation exists to handle efficiently."}]},
{"id":"PBQ-18","format":3,"domain":3,"obj":"3B3","title":"Choosing between compensating controls when the primary control cannot be implemented","brief":"A legacy application cannot support the organization's standard multi-factor authentication control due to a technical limitation, and the practitioner must recommend an appropriate compensating control design.","exhibitTitle":"WORKPAPER — COMPENSATING CONTROL OPTIONS","exhibit":"<span class='cy'>CONSTRAINT:</span> Legacy application cannot integrate with the\n  standard MFA solution; vendor confirms no near-term fix.\n<span class='cy'>OPTION 1:</span> Do nothing further since MFA is technically\n  infeasible.\n<span class='cy'>OPTION 2:</span> Restrict access to a hardened jump host requiring\n  MFA, with the legacy app reachable only from that host, plus enhanced\n  logging and session recording.\n<span class='cy'>OPTION 3:</span> Post a sign near the server reminding staff to use\n  strong passwords.","fields":[{"label":"Which option represents a properly designed compensating control?","hint":"Address the same risk objective through an alternate mechanism","options":["Option 1","Option 2, since it achieves an equivalent risk-reduction objective through an alternate technical mechanism","Option 3, since any documented reminder counts as a control"],"answer":1,"explain":"Option 2 is a genuine compensating control because it achieves the same underlying objective, strong authentication and monitored access, through an alternate mechanism (a hardened, MFA-protected jump host with logging) when the primary control cannot be directly implemented. Doing nothing further leaves the risk of weak, single-factor access to the legacy application completely untreated. A reminder sign is not a control at all; it has no enforceable mechanism and does not meaningfully reduce likelihood or impact."},{"label":"What must be documented for Option 2 to be considered a properly governed compensating control?","hint":"Compensating controls still require formal evaluation and approval","options":["Only the vendor's confirmation that MFA integration is infeasible","Nothing; deploying a technical workaround is sufficient by itself","The specific risk it addresses, why the primary control cannot be used, and formal approval by an authority with standing to accept the residual risk"],"answer":2,"explain":"A compensating control should be documented with the specific risk it addresses, the justification for why the primary control cannot be implemented, and formal approval by an authority with standing to accept whatever residual risk remains, mirroring the rigor expected of a formal exception. Deploying the technical workaround alone, without this documentation, leaves the decision ungoverned even if the mechanism itself is sound. The vendor's infeasibility confirmation explains the constraint but does not by itself constitute governance approval of the compensating approach."},{"label":"How should this compensating control be treated over time?","hint":"Compensating controls are not necessarily permanent","options":["As a permanent fixture requiring no further review, since it solves the problem","As a monitored, periodically reviewed measure, revisited as the legacy application nears retirement, replacement, or vendor support for MFA","As a temporary measure to be removed after 30 days regardless of circumstances"],"answer":1,"explain":"A compensating control addressing a technical constraint should be periodically reviewed, especially as the legacy application's retirement timeline, replacement plans, or eventual vendor MFA support may change the calculus, rather than being treated as permanently settled or ignored going forward. Treating it as needing no further review risks the same complacency that lets deficiencies persist unnoticed. An arbitrary fixed removal date unrelated to the application's actual lifecycle would force premature withdrawal of a still-necessary protection."}]},
{"id":"PBQ-19","format":3,"domain":3,"obj":"3B5","title":"Interpreting a control test result that shows partial effectiveness","brief":"A control test on automated account deprovisioning finds that it works correctly for most terminations but consistently fails for contractors terminated outside the standard HR workflow.","exhibitTitle":"WORKPAPER — CONTROL TEST RESULTS","exhibit":"<span class='cy'>CONTROL:</span> Automated deprovisioning triggered by HR\n  termination records within 24 hours.\n<span class='cy'>TEST SAMPLE:</span> 40 terminations tested; all 30 standard\n  employee terminations deprovisioned correctly within 24 hours.\n<span class='cy'>EXCEPTION:</span> All 10 contractor terminations, which are\n  processed outside the standard HR system, were not deprovisioned\n  for an average of 12 days.","fields":[{"label":"How should this control be rated based on the test results?","hint":"A single control can be effective for one population and not another","options":["Fully effective, since it worked for 30 of 40 cases tested (75%)","Effective for standard employee terminations but deficient for contractor terminations, which require a separate remediation track","Ineffective overall and should be entirely redesigned from scratch"],"answer":1,"explain":"The test results show the control performs correctly for the population it was actually designed to cover (standard HR-processed terminations) but fails entirely for contractors processed outside that workflow, so the accurate rating separates these two populations rather than blending them into one aggregate pass rate. Treating a 75% blended pass rate as \"fully effective\" masks a complete, systemic failure for an entire user population. Declaring the control entirely ineffective and needing a full redesign overstates the problem; the core mechanism works correctly for its intended population and only needs to be extended to cover contractors."},{"label":"What is the most likely root cause of the contractor deprovisioning gap?","hint":"The control's trigger doesn't reach this population","options":["Contractors are inherently less trustworthy than employees","The control's trigger is HR termination records, and contractors processed outside that system never generate the triggering event","The deprovisioning automation software has a licensing limit on contractor accounts"],"answer":1,"explain":"Because the control is designed to trigger off HR termination records, contractors whose terminations are processed through a separate, non-HR workflow never generate the event the automation depends on, which is a structural gap in trigger coverage rather than a flaw in trust or software licensing. The suggestion that contractors are inherently less trustworthy is an unfounded generalization with no basis in the test data. A licensing limit is not indicated anywhere in the exhibit and does not explain a consistent 12-day delay pattern."},{"label":"What remediation should the practitioner recommend?","hint":"Extend the trigger to cover the missed population","options":["Extend the deprovisioning trigger to include the contractor termination workflow, or route contractor terminations through the same HR system","Do nothing, since 75% of tested cases passed","Discontinue using contractors entirely to eliminate the gap"],"answer":0,"explain":"The direct remediation is to extend the automated trigger to also fire from the contractor termination workflow, or alternatively route contractor terminations through the same HR system that already triggers the control reliably, closing the structural gap. Accepting the current state because the blended pass rate looks acceptable ignores that an entire population is being missed consistently. Eliminating contractors entirely is a disproportionate business response to what is fundamentally a control-coverage gap, not a reason to change the organization's staffing model."}]},
{"id":"PBQ-20","format":3,"domain":3,"obj":"3C1","title":"Building a complete risk action plan","brief":"A risk action plan submitted for approval lists only a single line, \"implement stronger access controls,\" and the practitioner must determine what is missing before it can be considered executable.","exhibitTitle":"WORKPAPER — DRAFT RISK ACTION PLAN","exhibit":"<span class='cy'>RISK:</span> Excessive standing privileged access on the finance\n  reporting system, identified in the last quarterly review.\n<span class='cy'>SUBMITTED PLAN:</span> \"Implement stronger access controls.\"\n<span class='dim'>Note: no owner, budget, timeline, or success criteria were included.</span>","fields":[{"label":"What is the primary deficiency of the submitted plan?","hint":"An intention is not an executable commitment","options":["It is a statement of intent lacking an owner, resourcing, target date, and criteria to confirm the risk was actually reduced","It uses the phrase \"access controls\" instead of a more specific technical term","It should have been submitted as a PowerPoint instead of a text document"],"answer":0,"explain":"A complete risk action plan needs a named accountable owner, the resources or budget required, a realistic target completion date, and defined criteria for confirming the treatment achieved its intended risk reduction; this one-line submission has none of these and is therefore only a statement of intent, not an executable plan. The specific terminology used is a wording preference, not the substantive gap. The format of the submission (document type) is irrelevant to whether the plan is actually executable."},{"label":"Who should be named as the owner accountable for executing this action plan?","hint":"Delivery accountability should sit with someone who can act","options":["The risk practitioner who identified the finding","No one; action plans do not require a named owner if the risk is well understood","The individual or function with the authority and resources to actually implement the access-control changes, such as the finance system owner or an identity-governance lead"],"answer":2,"explain":"The owner should be whoever actually has the authority and resources to implement the change, such as the finance system owner or the identity-governance function, since that is who can be held accountable for delivery. The risk practitioner facilitates and tracks the plan but does not typically own operational execution of the fix itself. Every action plan requires a named owner; without one, there is no accountable party to hold responsible when the target date arrives."},{"label":"What should be used to confirm the action plan actually achieved its intended risk reduction once implemented?","hint":"Verify the outcome, not just that a task was marked complete","options":["A follow-up review or control test confirming standing privileged access has been reduced to the intended level","Simply marking the item \"complete\" in the tracking tool without further verification","Trusting the implementing team's verbal assurance that it is done"],"answer":0,"explain":"Confirming success requires an actual follow-up review or control test verifying that privileged access has been reduced to the intended level, closing the loop between the plan and its real risk-reduction outcome. Marking an item complete in a tracking tool records status but does not verify the underlying risk was actually addressed. A verbal assurance provides no independent evidence and is not a defensible basis for closing a documented risk finding."}]},
{"id":"PBQ-21","format":3,"domain":3,"obj":"3C3","title":"Selecting a key risk indicator that provides early warning","brief":"The practitioner must choose the best key risk indicator to provide advance warning of rising risk in the organization's patch management process, from a set of candidate metrics.","exhibitTitle":"WORKPAPER — CANDIDATE KRI OPTIONS","exhibit":"<span class='cy'>METRIC A:</span> Number of critical vulnerabilities remaining\n  unpatched beyond the defined SLA, trended monthly.\n<span class='cy'>METRIC B:</span> Total number of patches released by vendors\n  this month.\n<span class='cy'>METRIC C:</span> Number of patch management staff currently\n  employed.","fields":[{"label":"Which metric is the strongest KRI for early warning of rising patch-related risk?","hint":"A KRI should signal risk trending toward or past a threshold","options":["Metric A, since it directly tracks overdue critical vulnerabilities against a defined threshold and trend","Metric B, since more vendor patches always signal more organizational risk","Metric C, since staffing levels are the only thing that matters for patch management"],"answer":0,"explain":"Metric A directly measures the organization's own exposure, critical vulnerabilities that have breached the defined remediation SLA, trended over time, which is exactly what a KRI should do: give early warning as the metric approaches or exceeds a risk threshold. Metric B reflects vendor release volume, an external factor the organization does not control and which does not by itself indicate rising internal risk. Metric C is a resourcing input that may help explain a KRI breach but is not itself a measure of risk exposure."},{"label":"What should be defined alongside Metric A for it to function properly as a KRI?","hint":"Thresholds turn a metric into an actionable indicator","options":["A specific threshold value that, when breached, triggers a defined escalation or management response","Nothing further; simply reporting the raw count each month is sufficient","A requirement that the metric never be shared outside the patch management team"],"answer":0,"explain":"A KRI needs a defined threshold, so that breaching it triggers a specific, pre-agreed escalation or management response, turning the metric from a passive data point into an actionable early-warning indicator. Reporting the raw count without a threshold leaves no clear line between normal fluctuation and a genuine risk signal requiring action. Restricting the metric from wider visibility would defeat the purpose of a KRI, which exists specifically to inform risk owners and governance stakeholders."},{"label":"If Metric A begins trending upward for three consecutive months, what should the practitioner do?","hint":"A KRI trend is itself informative, even before threshold breach","options":["Wait until the metric fully breaches its threshold before taking any action or informing stakeholders","Flag the trend to the risk owner as an early warning, even before a full threshold breach, since a sustained upward trend itself indicates increasing risk","Discard the trend as noise since KRIs only matter at the moment of breach"],"answer":1,"explain":"A sustained upward trend across multiple periods is itself meaningful information a KRI is meant to surface, and flagging it to the risk owner before a full threshold breach allows for earlier intervention rather than waiting for the risk to fully materialize. Waiting silently until the threshold is breached forfeits the early-warning value that is the entire purpose of tracking a KRI over time. Dismissing a multi-month trend as noise ignores a real, sustained signal in favor of only reacting at the last possible moment."}]},
{"id":"PBQ-22","format":3,"domain":3,"obj":"3C6","title":"Choosing the right reporting artifact for a board-level audience","brief":"The practitioner must select the most appropriate reporting artifact to present the organization's overall IT risk posture to the board, which meets quarterly and has limited technical background.","exhibitTitle":"WORKPAPER — REPORTING ARTIFACT OPTIONS","exhibit":"<span class='cy'>OPTION 1:</span> A raw export of all 340 risk-register entries\n  with every field visible.\n<span class='cy'>OPTION 2:</span> A one-page executive risk dashboard showing\n  risk posture against appetite, top risks, and trend over the\n  last four quarters.\n<span class='cy'>OPTION 3:</span> A detailed technical vulnerability scan report\n  with CVE identifiers and CVSS scores.","fields":[{"label":"Which artifact BEST serves this board audience?","hint":"Translate detail into governance-relevant narrative","options":["Option 1, since more detail always demonstrates thoroughness to the board","Option 2, since it distills posture, top risks, and trend into a governance-relevant, non-technical view","Option 3, since technical precision is always the most credible form of reporting"],"answer":1,"explain":"A one-page executive dashboard summarizing risk posture against appetite, the top risks, and the trend over recent quarters gives the board exactly the governance-relevant information it needs to oversee risk without requiring technical translation on the spot. A raw 340-entry export overwhelms a non-technical board and obscures the handful of decisions that actually need governance attention. A technical vulnerability report full of CVE identifiers and CVSS scores is meaningless to a board without translation into business risk and trend, defeating the purpose of board reporting."},{"label":"What should accompany the dashboard's risk-posture-against-appetite view?","hint":"Context turns a metric into something actionable","options":["A brief narrative explaining what changed since the last report and why it matters to the business","Nothing; the dashboard's visuals are self-explanatory to any audience","A requirement that board members ask no questions during the presentation"],"answer":0,"explain":"A brief narrative explaining what changed since the last reporting period and why it matters to the business converts the dashboard's visuals into something the board can act on, rather than leaving them to guess at significance. Assuming the visuals are self-explanatory ignores that a non-technical audience needs interpretation to translate a chart into a governance decision. Discouraging board questions undermines the entire purpose of board oversight, which depends on genuine engagement and challenge, not passive reception of a report."},{"label":"How should the underlying 340-entry register relate to this board-level dashboard?","hint":"Detail still exists, just not at this altitude","options":["The register should be discarded once the dashboard is built, since the board only needs the summary","The register remains the detailed source of truth that the dashboard aggregates from and links back to for any item the board wants to drill into","The register and the dashboard should contain completely unrelated sets of risks"],"answer":1,"explain":"The detailed risk register remains the authoritative source of truth underlying the summarized dashboard, and the practitioner should be able to drill back into specific register entries if the board asks about a particular top risk, preserving traceability between summary and detail. Discarding the register once a dashboard exists would eliminate the operational record needed to actually manage individual risks day to day. The dashboard's content should be directly derived from the register, not an unrelated or independently maintained data set, or the two would drift out of sync and lose credibility."}]},
{"id":"PBQ-23","format":3,"domain":3,"obj":"3C7","title":"Reporting an escalating risk trend to the board mid-cycle","brief":"Between scheduled quarterly board meetings, a specific risk category has escalated sharply due to a new threat pattern, and the practitioner must decide whether and how to report it before the next scheduled meeting.","exhibitTitle":"WORKPAPER — MID-CYCLE ESCALATION DECISION","exhibit":"<span class='cy'>TREND:</span> Business email compromise attempts targeting the\n  finance department have tripled in six weeks; one near-miss\n  incident narrowly avoided a fraudulent wire transfer.\n<span class='cy'>NEXT SCHEDULED BOARD MEETING:</span> 10 weeks away.\n<span class='dim'>Note: the organization's board reporting policy defines out-of-cycle\n  triggers for material emerging risk.</span>","fields":[{"label":"Should this be reported before the next scheduled board meeting?","hint":"A material, escalating risk meets the definition of an out-of-cycle trigger","options":["No, routine reporting should always wait for the next scheduled quarterly cycle","Yes, this tripling trend and near-miss incident meets the profile of a material emerging risk warranting out-of-cycle reporting","No, since no actual fraudulent transfer succeeded, there is nothing material to report yet"],"answer":1,"explain":"A risk category tripling in six weeks with a near-miss incident against the finance function is exactly the kind of material, rapidly escalating risk the organization's own out-of-cycle reporting trigger is designed to capture, and waiting 10 weeks would leave the board uninformed of a live, worsening exposure. Waiting for the next scheduled cycle regardless of severity ignores that governance structures explicitly define exceptions for material developments precisely because a fixed quarterly cadence cannot always be responsive enough. Requiring an actual completed loss before reporting misses the point of an early-warning and governance-transparency obligation, which exists to inform the board before, not only after, a loss materializes."},{"label":"What should the out-of-cycle report to the board emphasize?","hint":"Business consequence and response, not just the raw event","options":["The specific technical configuration of the email filtering appliance","The trend, its potential business consequence, and the immediate and planned response actions","An extensive history of every phishing email received over the last five years"],"answer":1,"explain":"The report should focus on the trend itself, what it could cost the business if it succeeds, and what is being done immediately and going forward, which is the governance-relevant framing a board needs to decide whether further oversight or resourcing is warranted. Technical filtering configuration details are operational minutiae inappropriate for a board-level briefing. An exhaustive five-year phishing history is disproportionate detail that obscures the urgent, actionable point the board needs to understand right now."},{"label":"What should happen to the standing board reporting policy after this event?","hint":"Use the incident to validate or refine the trigger definition","options":["It should be reviewed to confirm the out-of-cycle trigger definition worked as intended and refined if any gap in timeliness was identified","It should be discarded since one incident occurred despite existing policy","Nothing; policies should never be revisited after they are first approved"],"answer":0,"explain":"Reviewing whether the trigger definition functioned as intended, and refining it if the escalation could have been reported even faster, is exactly the kind of continuous improvement a mature governance reporting policy requires. Discarding the policy over one incident overreacts, since the policy did in fact provide the mechanism used to escalate this risk appropriately. Treating policy as permanently fixed once approved contradicts the standard expectation that governance artifacts are periodically reviewed and improved based on real experience."}]},
{"id":"PBQ-24","format":3,"domain":3,"obj":"3C8","title":"Deciding whether an emerging threat warrants a new risk-register entry","brief":"A threat intelligence bulletin describes a novel attack technique already used against several industry peers, and the practitioner must decide how to handle it within the monitoring and reporting process for emerging risk.","exhibitTitle":"WORKPAPER — EMERGING THREAT INTAKE","exhibit":"<span class='cy'>BULLETIN:</span> New technique abuses a specific SaaS platform's\n  API integration feature to exfiltrate data; three industry peers\n  confirmed affected in the last month.\n<span class='cy'>INTERNAL CHECK:</span> The organization uses the same SaaS\n  platform and has the same API integration feature enabled.\n<span class='dim'>Note: no indicators of compromise have been found internally yet.</span>","fields":[{"label":"What should the practitioner do FIRST upon receiving this bulletin?","hint":"Relevance and exposure assessment precedes formal entry","options":["Assess whether the organization's own use of the affected platform and feature creates the same exposure described in the bulletin","Immediately disable the API integration feature enterprise-wide without further analysis","Dismiss the bulletin since no internal indicators of compromise have been found"],"answer":0,"explain":"The correct first step is to assess relevance: confirming the organization uses the same platform and has the same feature enabled establishes that the described exposure plausibly applies, which is the necessary basis for any further action. Disabling the feature enterprise-wide before assessing business impact and confirming the threat's applicability risks an disruptive, poorly justified change. Dismissing the bulletin because no indicators of compromise have been found yet ignores that the absence of detected exploitation does not mean the exposure does not exist; three peers have already been affected by this same technique."},{"label":"Given the confirmed exposure, what should happen to this item in the risk-monitoring process?","hint":"Confirmed relevance converts a threat bulletin into a tracked risk","options":["It should be logged as a new or updated risk-register entry, since the organization has confirmed the same asset and vulnerability the threat targets","It should remain informal and undocumented since it originated from an external bulletin, not an internal audit","It should only be tracked if a fourth industry peer is also affected"],"answer":0,"explain":"Once relevance and exposure are confirmed, the item should be captured formally in the risk register, since it represents a real risk to a specific asset and vulnerability the organization actually has, regardless of where the intelligence originated. Treating externally sourced intelligence as less worthy of formal tracking than internally discovered findings is an arbitrary distinction; source does not determine whether a risk deserves governance attention. Waiting for additional peers to be affected before tracking the risk internally delays action against a threat already confirmed to be both active and applicable."},{"label":"How should this emerging risk be reported relative to the standing risk register?","hint":"Emerging risk still needs a place in the overall reporting structure","options":["As a distinct, disconnected report that never integrates with the standing register or existing reporting cadence","Integrated into the existing risk register and reporting cadence, flagged appropriately given its emerging and rapidly evolving nature","It should not be reported at all until it is fully resolved"],"answer":1,"explain":"The emerging risk should be integrated into the standing risk register and existing reporting cadence, flagged to reflect its emerging, rapidly evolving nature so it receives appropriately frequent reassessment rather than being managed outside the organization's normal risk governance structure. Keeping it as a disconnected, separate report fragments risk visibility and undermines the integrated, single-register approach that supports enterprise-wide prioritization. Withholding any reporting until the risk is fully resolved contradicts the entire purpose of ongoing risk monitoring and reporting, which exists to give stakeholders visibility while a risk is still active, not only after it concludes."}]},
{"id":"PBQ-25","format":4,"domain":4,"obj":"4A2","title":"Evaluating a request to bypass change management for an urgent DevOps release","brief":"A DevOps team wants to push a hotfix directly to production without the standard change-management approval, arguing that the automated CI/CD pipeline's tests provide sufficient assurance on their own.","exhibitTitle":"WORKPAPER — CHANGE MANAGEMENT BYPASS REQUEST","exhibit":"<span class='cy'>REQUEST:</span> Deploy an urgent hotfix directly to production,\n  bypassing the standard change-approval gate, citing pipeline test\n  coverage as sufficient assurance.\n<span class='cy'>CONTEXT:</span> The affected system processes regulated\n  transactions; the hotfix touches transaction-validation logic.\n<span class='dim'>Note: automated tests cover functional correctness but not\n  segregation-of-duties or independent review requirements.</span>","fields":[{"label":"What is the risk practitioner's BEST response to this request?","hint":"Automated testing and governance requirements serve different purposes","options":["Approve the bypass since automated pipeline tests are inherently more reliable than manual review","Recommend an expedited but still governed change path, such as emergency change approval with post-implementation review, rather than bypassing governance entirely","Block the release entirely until the next standard release cycle regardless of urgency"],"answer":1,"explain":"An expedited emergency-change path that still requires appropriate approval and mandates post-implementation review balances the legitimate urgency with the segregation-of-duties and independent oversight that automated functional tests do not provide, especially for a system processing regulated transactions. Approving a full bypass conflates functional test coverage with governance assurance; passing unit and integration tests does not confirm the change was independently reviewed or appropriately authorized. Blocking the release until the next standard cycle ignores the genuine urgency and may leave a known defect unpatched longer than necessary when a faster, still-governed path exists."},{"label":"Why is automated pipeline test coverage insufficient assurance on its own for this change?","hint":"Tests validate function, not governance","options":["Because automated tests take too long to run for an urgent fix","Because automated tests can never be trusted for any type of change","Because pipeline tests validate functional correctness but do not substitute for independent review, segregation of duties, or documented approval that governance requires"],"answer":2,"explain":"Automated tests confirm the code behaves as functionally intended, but they do not provide the independent human review, segregation of duties, or documented authorization that change governance exists to ensure, particularly for a change touching regulated transaction-validation logic. Automated tests are a valuable and generally trustworthy control for functional correctness; the issue is scope, not reliability, since they were never designed to substitute for governance review. Test execution speed is not the basis for the concern here; the concern is what the tests do and do not validate."},{"label":"What should be documented once the emergency change is deployed?","hint":"Emergency paths still require a paper trail","options":["Nothing, since the urgency of the situation excuses documentation requirements","The justification for the emergency path, who approved it, and the outcome of the mandatory post-implementation review","Only the code diff, with no record of the approval or review process"],"answer":1,"explain":"Even an expedited emergency change should be documented with its justification, the approver, and the results of the required post-implementation review, preserving the accountability trail that governance depends on regardless of how urgent the original request was. Urgency does not excuse documentation; in fact, emergency paths are exactly where a clear record matters most since normal controls were compressed or adjusted. Recording only the code diff omits the governance context, approval, and review outcome needed to demonstrate the change was properly authorized and later validated."}]},
{"id":"PBQ-26","format":4,"domain":4,"obj":"4A6","title":"Choosing between RTO-driven recovery strategies","brief":"The BIA has established a 2-hour recovery time objective for the order-processing system, and the practitioner must select a recovery strategy capable of actually meeting that target.","exhibitTitle":"WORKPAPER — RECOVERY STRATEGY OPTIONS","exhibit":"<span class='cy'>BIA FINDING:</span> Order-processing system RTO = 2 hours;\n  RPO = 15 minutes.\n<span class='cy'>OPTION 1:</span> Cold site requiring equipment procurement and\n  a rebuild from backup tapes; estimated recovery time 3-5 days.\n<span class='cy'>OPTION 2:</span> Active-active architecture across two regions\n  with continuous data replication; estimated failover time under\n  10 minutes.\n<span class='cy'>OPTION 3:</span> Warm site with daily backup restoration;\n  estimated recovery time 8-12 hours.","fields":[{"label":"Which option can actually meet the stated RTO and RPO?","hint":"Match the technical capability to the business requirement","options":["Option 1, since cold sites are the most cost-effective choice regardless of RTO","Option 2, since active-active replication with sub-10-minute failover meets both the 2-hour RTO and the 15-minute RPO","Option 3, since 8-12 hours is close enough to 2 hours for most practical purposes"],"answer":1,"explain":"Option 2's active-active architecture with continuous replication and sub-10-minute failover comfortably meets both the 2-hour RTO and the 15-minute RPO, making it the only option that actually satisfies the business requirement established by the BIA. Option 1's 3-5 day recovery time is drastically longer than the 2-hour RTO regardless of its cost advantage; cost cannot justify choosing a strategy that fails the stated requirement. Option 3's 8-12 hour recovery is still four to six times longer than the 2-hour RTO; \"close enough\" is not a valid basis when the BIA has established a specific, business-derived target."},{"label":"Why must RPO be evaluated separately from RTO when selecting this strategy?","hint":"They measure different dimensions of recoverability","options":["RPO only matters for systems that do not process financial transactions","RTO and RPO always move together and never need separate evaluation","RTO measures how fast the system is restored while RPO measures how much data loss is tolerable, and a strategy can satisfy one without satisfying the other"],"answer":2,"explain":"RTO and RPO measure genuinely different dimensions, recovery speed versus tolerable data loss, so a strategy must be evaluated against both independently; a fast failover that restores service quickly but loses hours of transactions would meet RTO while badly failing RPO. Assuming they always move together is incorrect and is precisely why a daily-backup warm site can fail an RPO of 15 minutes even if its RTO were otherwise acceptable. RPO applies to any system where data currency matters, not only financial-transaction systems; the concept is general to data-loss tolerance."},{"label":"What should happen if the selected recovery strategy's cost significantly exceeds prior budget assumptions?","hint":"Cost tension is resolved by revisiting the business requirement, not ignoring it","options":["Silently select a cheaper option that does not meet the RTO/RPO and hope an incident does not occur","Present the cost-requirement tradeoff to the business owner, since only the business can decide whether to fund the strategy or formally revise the RTO/RPO","Automatically approve the more expensive option without any business discussion, since technical staff always prioritize resilience over cost"],"answer":1,"explain":"When the technically necessary strategy costs more than expected, the practitioner should surface the tradeoff to the accountable business owner, since only the business can decide to fund the higher-cost solution or formally revise the RTO/RPO to a target a cheaper strategy can actually meet. Quietly choosing an inadequate, cheaper option accepts a real recovery-capability gap without any deliberate, informed decision by the party who owns that risk. Approving the expensive option unilaterally bypasses the business owner's authority over cost-risk tradeoffs, which is exactly the kind of decision that should not be made by technical staff alone."}]},
{"id":"PBQ-27","format":4,"domain":4,"obj":"4A7","title":"Assessing risk from a business unit's shadow use of generative AI","brief":"An internal audit discovers that a business unit has been pasting customer contract text into a public generative AI tool to draft summaries, with no data-handling review or approval.","exhibitTitle":"WORKPAPER — SHADOW AI USE FINDING","exhibit":"<span class='cy'>FINDING:</span> Marketing and sales staff routinely paste\n  customer contract excerpts, including pricing and terms, into a\n  public generative AI chatbot to draft summaries.\n<span class='cy'>POLICY STATE:</span> No acceptable-use policy for AI tools\n  currently exists; no approved AI tool has been vetted.\n<span class='dim'>Note: the public tool's terms of service permit using submitted\n  content to improve the vendor's models.</span>","fields":[{"label":"What is the core risk this finding represents?","hint":"Confidential data leaving the organization's control","options":["Confidential contract data may be retained or used by the AI vendor to improve its models, outside the organization's control and without customer consent","The staff are being more productive than expected, which itself is the risk","The AI tool's summaries might contain minor grammatical errors"],"answer":0,"explain":"Because the public tool's terms permit using submitted content to improve its models, pasting confidential contract data, including pricing and terms, exposes that information to retention and use entirely outside the organization's control and without any customer consent for that disclosure. Increased productivity is not itself a risk; the concern is what confidential data is being exposed to achieve it. Minor summary quality issues are a trivial concern compared to the confidentiality and contractual exposure created by uncontrolled data submission to a third-party AI service."},{"label":"What should the organization do FIRST in response to this finding?","hint":"Stop the ongoing exposure while building a durable control","options":["Immediately terminate the staff involved without further investigation","Assess the scope of data already exposed, halt the unsanctioned practice, and establish an acceptable-use policy with vetted, approved AI tool options","Ignore the finding since generative AI is now common industry practice"],"answer":1,"explain":"The organization should first understand how much confidential data has already been exposed, stop the ongoing practice, and then establish a governed acceptable-use policy that channels staff toward vetted AI tools with appropriate data-handling terms, addressing both the immediate exposure and the systemic policy gap. Terminating staff without investigation is a disproportionate, punitive response to a governance gap that existed because no policy or approved tool was ever provided in the first place. Dismissing the finding because generative AI use is common elsewhere ignores the organization's own specific confidentiality and contractual obligations regarding this customer data."},{"label":"What should the eventual AI acceptable-use policy require for any approved tool?","hint":"Vendor terms must be evaluated, not assumed","options":["A review of the vendor's data-handling and retention terms to confirm submitted data is not used to train models or retained beyond an acceptable period","No review is necessary as long as the tool is popular and widely used","A requirement that only executives are permitted to use any AI tool"],"answer":0,"explain":"An acceptable-use policy should require that any approved AI tool's data-handling and retention terms are actually reviewed and confirmed not to use submitted data for model training or indefinite retention, addressing the exact exposure this finding revealed. Popularity of a tool says nothing about its data-handling terms and is not a substitute for actually reviewing them. Restricting AI use to executives only does not address the underlying data-handling risk and would not meet the legitimate business need for broader, appropriately governed staff use."}]},
{"id":"PBQ-28","format":4,"domain":4,"obj":"4B2","title":"Selecting the appropriate access control model for a new claims system","brief":"A new insurance claims system needs an access control model, and the practitioner must recommend the model that best fits the organization's requirement for fine-grained, context-aware access decisions.","exhibitTitle":"WORKPAPER — ACCESS CONTROL MODEL SELECTION","exhibit":"<span class='cy'>REQUIREMENT:</span> Access should depend on the combination\n  of the user's department, the claim's classification level, and\n  whether the request occurs during approved business hours.\n<span class='cy'>OPTION 1:</span> Role-Based Access Control (RBAC) — access\n  tied to a fixed set of job-function roles only.\n<span class='cy'>OPTION 2:</span> Attribute-Based Access Control (ABAC) — access\n  evaluated against multiple attributes (user, resource, environment)\n  in combination.\n<span class='cy'>OPTION 3:</span> Discretionary Access Control (DAC) — resource\n  owners individually grant access at their own discretion.","fields":[{"label":"Which access control model BEST satisfies this multi-attribute, context-aware requirement?","hint":"Match the model to the number of independent conditions being evaluated","options":["Option 1 (RBAC), since role assignment is always sufficient for any access scenario","Option 2 (ABAC), since it can evaluate department, classification level, and time-of-access together as combined conditions","Option 3 (DAC), since individual owner discretion is always the most secure approach"],"answer":1,"explain":"ABAC is designed specifically to evaluate multiple independent attributes together, such as department, resource classification, and environmental context like time of access, making it the correct fit for this multi-condition requirement that a simple role assignment cannot express. RBAC ties access to a fixed role definition and struggles to natively express conditions like time-of-day or a dynamic data-classification attribute without significant role proliferation. DAC's owner-discretion model is inconsistent and difficult to govern at scale; it is not inherently more secure and does not address the specific multi-attribute requirement described here."},{"label":"What is a key governance risk of Option 3 (DAC) if it were chosen instead?","hint":"Discretion without oversight erodes consistency","options":["Individual owners granting access at their own discretion can produce inconsistent, unaudited access decisions with no enterprise-wide policy enforcement","DAC is risk-free because owners always understand data sensitivity perfectly","DAC automatically enforces the same classification-based rules as ABAC"],"answer":0,"explain":"Discretionary access control's core governance weakness is that individual resource owners make access decisions independently, which can produce inconsistent outcomes with no centralized, auditable enforcement of enterprise-wide classification or time-based policy, undermining consistent risk management across the organization. Claiming DAC is risk-free assumes owners always correctly judge sensitivity and consequence, which is an unfounded and frequently violated assumption. DAC does not automatically enforce classification-based rules the way ABAC's attribute evaluation does; it depends entirely on each individual owner's own judgment."},{"label":"Once ABAC is implemented, what ongoing control activity is essential to keep it effective?","hint":"Attribute-driven policies must be validated as conditions change","options":["Periodic review and testing of the attribute policies to confirm they still produce correct access decisions as roles, classifications, and business hours change","No ongoing review is needed once the attribute rules are initially configured","Only the environmental (time-of-access) attribute needs periodic review; user and resource attributes are static"],"answer":0,"explain":"Because ABAC decisions depend on multiple attributes that can each change over time, department reassignments, reclassification of claims, or shifts in approved business hours, the policies must be periodically reviewed and tested to confirm they continue to produce correct access decisions as those underlying conditions evolve. Assuming no review is needed after initial configuration ignores that attribute values are not static and can drift out of alignment with actual risk over time. All three attribute categories, not just the environmental one, can change and therefore all warrant periodic validation, not just the time-based condition."}]},
{"id":"PBQ-29","format":4,"domain":4,"obj":"4A3","title":"Deciding when security requirements should enter the SDLC","brief":"A development team is debating whether security requirements should be defined during initial design or added as a final testing gate before an application's production release.","exhibitTitle":"WORKPAPER — SDLC SECURITY TIMING DEBATE","exhibit":"<span class='cy'>PROPOSAL A:</span> Define security requirements during the\n  initial design phase, alongside functional and performance\n  requirements.\n<span class='cy'>PROPOSAL B:</span> Add a dedicated security testing gate just\n  before production deployment, after development is complete.\n<span class='dim'>Note: the application processes regulated customer financial data.</span>","fields":[{"label":"Which proposal reflects sound risk practice for the SDLC?","hint":"Cost and effectiveness of remediation depend heavily on when a gap is found","options":["Proposal A, since defining requirements early avoids costly late-stage rework and design-level flaws that a final gate cannot fully remediate","Proposal B, since a single late testing gate is just as effective as early requirements and simpler to manage","Neither; security requirements should be left to individual developer discretion throughout"],"answer":0,"explain":"Defining security requirements during initial design, alongside functional and performance requirements, is far more cost-effective and catches architectural-level risks that a late testing gate cannot fix without significant rework, which matters even more for an application handling regulated financial data. A final testing gate alone finds problems only after most design and development investment has already been made, when fixing a structural flaw is dramatically more expensive and may force a difficult choice between delaying release or shipping known weaknesses. Leaving requirements to individual developer discretion produces inconsistent, unaccountable outcomes with no defined baseline the organization can govern or audit."},{"label":"What is the main risk of relying solely on Proposal B's late-stage gate for a system handling regulated data?","hint":"Some findings cannot be cheaply fixed after the fact","options":["Late-stage testing gates are always faster than early design reviews","There is no meaningful difference in risk between the two proposals","Findings discovered just before release are costly and time-pressured to fix, risking a rushed decision to delay the release or accept the risk of shipping known gaps"],"answer":2,"explain":"Discovering security gaps at a final gate right before release creates intense time pressure, often forcing an unenviable choice between delaying a committed release date or accepting the risk of deploying with a known, unremediated weakness in a system processing regulated financial data. The claim that late testing is always faster is false and is precisely why late discovery creates schedule risk in the first place. There is a material difference between the two approaches, since one prevents costly structural issues from being built in at all while the other only detects them after the fact."},{"label":"How should security requirements for this regulated system be sourced during design?","hint":"Draw from applicable regulatory and organizational baselines","options":["From whichever security requirements the development team happens to already be familiar with","From a generic checklist unrelated to the specific data type or regulatory context","From applicable regulatory obligations for financial data plus the organization's own security baseline and architecture standards"],"answer":2,"explain":"Because the system processes regulated financial data, its security requirements should be sourced from the specific applicable regulatory obligations together with the organization's own security baseline and architecture standards, ensuring the requirements actually match this system's real risk and compliance context. Relying only on what the development team already happens to know risks missing regulatory-specific requirements that fall outside their existing familiarity. A generic, context-unaware checklist is unlikely to capture the specific obligations tied to regulated financial data and may create a false sense that requirements were adequately addressed."}]},
{"id":"PBQ-30","format":4,"domain":4,"obj":"4B4","title":"Applying privacy-by-design principles to a new analytics feature","brief":"A product team wants to add a new analytics feature that collects granular user location data by default, and the practitioner must evaluate the proposal against data-privacy and data-protection principles before it proceeds.","exhibitTitle":"WORKPAPER — ANALYTICS FEATURE PRIVACY REVIEW","exhibit":"<span class='cy'>PROPOSAL:</span> Collect precise, continuous location data from\n  all users by default to power a new analytics dashboard; opt-out\n  buried three menus deep in settings.\n<span class='cy'>STATED BUSINESS NEED:</span> Aggregate, city-level usage trends\n  for the dashboard; individual precise location is not required for\n  the stated purpose.","fields":[{"label":"What is the core privacy principle this proposal violates?","hint":"Collect only what the stated purpose actually requires","options":["Data minimization and purpose limitation, since precise continuous location is collected by default when only aggregate, city-level data is needed for the stated purpose","There is no violation, since more granular data always produces better analytics","Encryption strength, since the proposal does not specify an encryption algorithm"],"answer":0,"explain":"The proposal violates data minimization and purpose limitation by collecting far more granular data, precise continuous location, than the stated business purpose actually requires, which only needs aggregate, city-level trends. Assuming more granular data is always better ignores that privacy principles specifically require limiting collection to what a stated purpose actually needs, not whatever might be maximally useful. The concern here is about what data is collected and why, not the technical strength of any encryption applied to it, which is a separate and secondary control question."},{"label":"What should be changed about the default collection and consent design?","hint":"Privacy-by-design favors minimal collection and clear consent by default","options":["Collect only the city-level or aggregated data actually needed for the stated purpose, and make any more granular data collection an informed, opt-in choice rather than a buried opt-out","Keep the default as-is but make the opt-out one menu shallower","Require users to contact support by phone to opt out of location collection"],"answer":0,"explain":"A privacy-by-design approach collects only the aggregated, city-level data the stated purpose actually requires by default, and treats more granular, precise collection as something users must knowingly and affirmatively opt into, rather than defaulting to maximal collection with a hard-to-find opt-out. Making the opt-out only marginally easier to find does not address the deeper problem of over-collection by default; the default itself should minimize data collected. Requiring a phone call to opt out adds unnecessary friction and moves further from the transparent, user-respecting consent design that privacy-by-design principles require."},{"label":"Why does burying the opt-out three menus deep raise an additional concern beyond over-collection?","hint":"Meaningful consent requires genuine accessibility","options":["It does not raise any additional concern beyond the collection issue itself","It undermines meaningful, informed consent, since users cannot exercise a real choice over data they may not know is being collected or how to stop it","Menu depth is a user-experience issue with no privacy relevance"],"answer":1,"explain":"Burying the opt-out deep in settings undermines meaningful, informed consent, since a choice that is practically undiscoverable does not give users a genuine opportunity to control data collection they may not even realize is happening. Claiming there is no additional concern ignores that consent accessibility and collection scope are two distinct, both-relevant privacy dimensions. Menu depth is not purely a user-experience detail here; it directly affects whether the consent mechanism is genuine or merely a formality designed to be difficult to exercise."}]}
]);
